{
  "info": {
    "name": "Automation Exercise API",
    "_postman_id": "ae-api-portfolio-v1",
    "description": "Complete coverage of the 14 documented public endpoints on https://automationexercise.com/api_list — part of the QA Engineer Portfolio.\n\n## Important quirk\n\nThe AE API **always returns HTTP 200**, even for client errors (400, 404, 405). The *real* status is in the `responseCode` field of the JSON body. Every test in this collection asserts BOTH:\n\n1. `pm.response.to.have.status(200)` — confirms the API endpoint is reachable\n2. `body.responseCode === <expected>` — confirms the business-level outcome\n\nThis is unusual but documented behavior. The split assertion is the right model: it lets us distinguish between the API being down (HTTP != 200) and the API returning a business error (HTTP 200, responseCode 400/404/405).\n\n## Folder layout\n\n- **Health & Discovery** — read-only listing endpoints (products, brands)\n- **Search** — search by keyword, with and without the required parameter\n- **Authentication** — `verifyLogin` happy path and all documented negative cases\n- **Method Not Allowed** — endpoints that explicitly reject certain HTTP verbs\n- **User Lifecycle** — chained create → fetch → update → delete with timestamped data so the chain is idempotent across runs\n\n## Environment\n\nUses `environments/automation-exercise.postman_environment.json`. Key variables: `baseUrl`, `apiPath`, `registeredEmail`, `registeredPassword`, `createdUserEmail`, `createdUserPassword`.",
    "schema": "https://schema.getpostman.com/json/collection/v2.1.0/collection.json"
  },
  "item": [
    {
      "name": "Health & Discovery",
      "description": "Public read-only endpoints. No authentication, no body required.",
      "item": [
        {
          "name": "API 1 — GET /productsList",
          "request": {
            "method": "GET",
            "header": [],
            "url": {
              "raw": "{{baseUrl}}{{apiPath}}/productsList",
              "host": ["{{baseUrl}}{{apiPath}}"],
              "path": ["productsList"]
            },
            "description": "Returns the full catalog. The portfolio asserts that the products array exists and has at least one item — a thin schema contract."
          },
          "event": [
            {
              "listen": "test",
              "script": {
                "type": "text/javascript",
                "exec": [
                  "pm.test('HTTP status is 200', () => {",
                  "  pm.response.to.have.status(200);",
                  "});",
                  "",
                  "pm.test('responseCode in body is 200', () => {",
                  "  const body = pm.response.json();",
                  "  pm.expect(body.responseCode).to.equal(200);",
                  "});",
                  "",
                  "pm.test('Body has products array with at least one product', () => {",
                  "  const body = pm.response.json();",
                  "  pm.expect(body).to.have.property('products');",
                  "  pm.expect(body.products).to.be.an('array').that.is.not.empty;",
                  "});",
                  "",
                  "pm.test('Each product has id, name, price, brand, category', () => {",
                  "  const body = pm.response.json();",
                  "  const first = body.products[0];",
                  "  pm.expect(first).to.include.keys('id', 'name', 'price', 'brand', 'category');",
                  "});",
                  "",
                  "pm.test('Response time is under 5s', () => {",
                  "  pm.expect(pm.response.responseTime).to.be.below(5000);",
                  "});"
                ]
              }
            }
          ]
        },
